  "text": "Relative proportion of likes and dislikes-Of particular interest was the relative proportion of like and dislike attitudes. Excluded from further analyses were attitude segments coded as unclear (4%), such as \"I can't think of any [likes or dislikes].\"and \"I don't know whether it's a like or dislike.\" Counter to the stereotype that older adults hold negative opinions about technology, participants expressed significantly more likes than dislikes when discussing technologies used in the home (60% vs. 36% of the total segments, χ 2 (1) = 69.07, p < .01), for work (59% vs. 37%, χ 2 (1) = 40.88, p < .01) and for health (60% vs. 35%, χ 2 (1) = 37.79, p < .01). Note that due to the phrasing of the question it is possible that participants were primed to produce more likes because the word \"like\" preceded the word \"dislike.\" Nonetheless, the majority of older adults' attitudes were positive, suggesting that they perceived the benefits of using technology to outweigh the costs, regardless of domain. This finding is consistent with the results of [CITATION_1] , which showed that perception of benefit was more indicative of acceptance than perception of cost.",
